**Sec. 50101. Onshore Oil and Gas Leasing.**
The Secretary of the Interior must immediately resume quarterly onshore oil and gas lease sales in nine specific states: Wyoming, New Mexico, Colorado, Utah, Montana, North Dakota, Oklahoma, Nevada, and Alaska. For each sale, the Secretary is required to offer at least 50 percent of available parcels nominated for development under existing resource management plans. The bill repeals specific Inflation Reduction Act provisions regarding royalty rates and noncompetitive leasing, restoring previous laws as if they had never been amended. Additionally, the Secretary must conduct replacement sales within the same fiscal year if a sale is canceled or if 25 percent or more of the offered acreage receives no bids.

**Sec. 50102. Offshore Oil and Gas Leasing.**
The Secretary of the Interior must conduct a minimum of 30 region-wide lease sales in the Gulf of America region and 6 sales in the Cook Inlet Planning Area of Alaska between 2025 and 2040. Lease terms for the Gulf of America must match those of Sale 254, with royalty rates set between 12.5 percent and 16.67 percent, and a primary term of 10 years for leases in waters deeper than 800 meters. For Alaska sales, 70 percent of revenues derived from leases issued after fiscal year 2034 will be paid to the State of Alaska, while the remaining 30 percent goes to the Treasury. The bill also mandates that the Secretary approve commingling requests for multiple reservoirs in a single wellbore unless safety or recovery reduction is conclusively proven.

**Sec. 50103. Royalties on Extracted Methane.**
This section repeals Section 50263 of Public Law 117-169, which previously established a royalty rate on extracted methane, effectively restoring the prior legal framework regarding methane royalties.

**Sec. 50104. Alaska Oil and Gas Leasing.**
The Secretary of the Interior must conduct at least four area-wide lease sales on the Coastal Plain of Alaska within 10 years of enactment, offering not fewer than 400,000 acres per sale. The initial sale must occur within one year, with subsequent sales scheduled for years three, five, and seven after enactment. Revenue sharing is adjusted so that 50 percent of receipts go to the State of Alaska for fiscal years 2025 through 2033, increasing to 70 percent for fiscal year 2034 and thereafter.

**Sec. 50105. National Petroleum Reserve-Alaska.**
The Secretary of the Interior must restore and resume oil and gas lease sales in the National Petroleum Reserve-Alaska (NPR-A), conducting at least five sales within 10 years of enactment. Each sale must offer not fewer than 4,000,000 acres, with the first sale occurring within one year and additional sales occurring every two years thereafter. Beginning in fiscal year 2034, 70 percent of receipts from these leases will be paid to the State of Alaska, with the remaining 30 percent deposited into the Treasury.

**Sec. 50201. Coal Leasing.**
The Secretary of the Interior must process qualified coal lease applications within 90 days of enactment, including publishing environmental reviews, establishing fair market value, and holding lease sales. The Secretary is authorized to grant additional approvals for previously issued coal leases to allow mining activities to commence. If a qualified applicant submits the winning bid, the Secretary must issue the lease to that person.

**Sec. 50202. Coal Royalty.**
The coal royalty rate is temporarily reduced to a maximum of 7 percent for the period beginning on the date of enactment and ending on September 30, 2034, reverting to 12.5 percent thereafter. This rate reduction applies to all existing coal leases that have not been terminated. Lessees who paid advance royalties prior to enactment will receive a credit for the difference between the amount paid and the amount required under the new rate.

**Sec. 50203. Leases for Known Recoverable Coal Resources.**
The Secretary of the Interior must make available for lease at least 4,000,000 additional acres of known recoverable coal resources on Federal land within 90 days of enactment. These lands must be located in the 48 contiguous States and Alaska but are explicitly excluded from National Monuments, National Recreation Areas, Wilderness areas, and other protected systems.

**Sec. 50204. Authorization to Mine Federal Coal.**
Federal coal reserves adjacent to State or private land are authorized for mining if access is necessary to mine economically, provided a mining plan was previously approved by the Secretary. The Secretary must take necessary steps to authorize this mining within 90 days of enactment without substantial modification to existing plans. This authorization does not prevent a review under the National Environmental Policy Act.

**Sec. 50301. Timber Sales and Long-Term Contracting for the Forest Service and the Bureau of Land Management.**
The Secretary of Agriculture must increase annual timber sales on National Forest System land by at least 250,000,000 board-feet each year from 2026 through 2034 compared to the previous year. The Secretary of the Interior must similarly increase annual timber sales on public lands by at least 20,000,000 board-feet annually during the same period. Both agencies are required to enter into at least 40 long-term contracts for the Forest Service and 5 for the Bureau of Land Management, each lasting a minimum of 20 years. All monies derived from these contracts must be deposited into the general fund of the Treasury.

**Sec. 50302. Renewable Energy Fees on Federal Land.**
The Secretary must collect acreage rent for wind and solar rights-of-way based on a formula involving pastureland rental rates, an encumbrance factor (100% for solar, at least 10% for wind), and an annual 3% adjustment factor. A capacity fee must also be collected annually, calculated as the greater of the acreage rent or 3.9 percent of the gross proceeds from electricity sales. Wind energy projects may request a 10-percent reduction in the capacity fee if at least 25 percent of the land is used for other authorized activities.

**Sec. 50303. Renewable Energy Revenue Sharing.**
Beginning January 1, 2026, 25 percent of revenues from renewable energy projects on covered land will be paid to the State where the revenue is derived, and another 25 percent will be distributed to the counties based on the percentage of land generating the revenue. These payments are deposited in the general fund of the Treasury and allocated without further appropriation or fiscal year limitation. Payments to counties are in addition to any payments in lieu of taxes they may already receive.

**Sec. 50304. Rescission of National Park Service and Bureau of Land Management Funds.**
The unobligated balances of funds made available by Sections 50221, 50222, and 50223 of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 are rescinded.

**Sec. 50305. Celebrating America's 250th Anniversary.**
The Secretary of the Interior is appropriated $150,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to fund events and activities commemorating the 250th anniversary of the founding of the United States. These funds remain available through fiscal year 2028 and are to be used for the observance and commemoration of this milestone.

**Sec. 50401. Strategic Petroleum Reserve.**
The Department of Energy is appropriated $218,000,000 for maintenance and repairs of Strategic Petroleum Reserve facilities and $171,000,000 to acquire petroleum products for storage in fiscal year 2025. These funds remain available until September 30, 2029. The bill also repeals the mandate in Public Law 115-97 that required the drawdown and sale of Strategic Petroleum Reserve oil.

**Sec. 50402. Repeals; Rescissions.**
Section 50142 of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 is repealed, and its unobligated balance is rescinded. Additionally, unobligated balances from Sections 50123, 50141, 50144, 50145, 50151, 50152, 50153, and 50161 of the same Act are rescinded.

**Sec. 50403. Energy Dominance Financing.**
The Energy Policy Act of 2005 is amended to allow financing for activities that increase capacity, output, or provide electric supply to maintain grid reliability. The Secretary of Energy is appropriated $1,000,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to carry out these activities, with funds remaining available through September 30, 2028. The Secretary may use up to 3 percent of these funds for administrative expenses. The commitment authority for certain projects is extended from 2026 to 2028.

**Sec. 50404. Transformational Artificial Intelligence Models.**
The Secretary of Energy must mobilize National Laboratories to curate and structure scientific data for use in artificial intelligence and machine learning models. Seed efforts will be initiated to develop self-improving AI models for science and engineering, which will be shared via the American science cloud. These models are intended to accelerate the development of next-generation microelectronics and new energy technologies. $150,000,000 is appropriated for fiscal year 2025 to carry out these activities, remaining available through September 30, 2026.

**Sec. 50501. Water Conveyance and Surface Water Storage Enhancement.**
The Secretary of the Interior is appropriated $1,000,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to restore or increase the capacity of existing Bureau of Reclamation conveyance and surface water storage facilities. These funds remain available through September 30, 2034, and contracts entered into under this section are not treated as new or amended contracts for certain Reclamation Reform Act purposes. None of the funds provided are reimbursable or subject to matching or cost-sharing requirements. [end of text]


